description: This was my first time seeing a Post oak in the fall.  I had seen one small sapling out in the central pine barrens of Long Island this summer.  This was one of several Post oaks here, at the northern section of Pelham Bay Park, well weathered by the winds and the salt air of the Long Island Sound.  The crimson leaves were a sight to behold!  The lower surfaces of the leaves were pink and velvety, with stellate (star shaped) hairs visible under a hand lens - presumably where the name Quercus stellata comes from.  The leaves, with their distinctive, asymmetrical lobed shape - wide near the apex and narrow near the point of attachment - eventually will turn a warm pinkish brown color when they fall, as seen in some of the photos. The twigs were tan, fuzzy and had small reddish brown, round buds.  The bark was flaky, reminiscent of Quercus alba.  The windward side of the tree was missing much of the bark.  The tree had a scraggly, scruffy, asymmetrical look to it and branches were missing.

description: Posting this because of the unusual timing and weather conditions. Witnessed this kestrel eating what appeared to be an Italian wall lizard on the landfill at Pelham Bay Park (where these lizards are common). The temperature was 30 degrees with really intense winds  so this lizard should have been nine inches underground! This was on Sunday morning. On Friday, two days before, the temperature quickly dropped from 55F to 39 F over the course of 5 to 6 hours in the middle of the day. I speculate that the lizard was out enjoying the balmy mid-fifties weather and didnt make it back into the ground in time for the cold snap, to be found by the kestrel two days later.
